#1 Adenocarcinoma of the descending colon
As Ms. Marcantel's right-side of the colon was unable to be visualized due to the near obstructing mass lesion in her left colon, we would recommend a colonoscopy to be attempted in the complex suite in order to rule-out any synchronous lesions.  At the time of colonoscopy, tissue samples will be obtained in order to be read by our pathologists.  We will also make arrangements for the patient to undergo PET scan due to the concerning lesions in the right adrenal gland as well as the posterior segment of the right lobe of the liver.  Ms. Marcantel is scheduled to see Dr. Jennings in Colorectal Surgery for further evaluation and recommendations regarding laparoscopic surgery.  If and when Ms. Marcantel is scheduled for surgery, she is OK to proceed with general anesthesia.  We have explained to the patient and her husband that final tumor staging would be done post-operatively.  If indicated, further discussions of chemotherapy would be performed by the medical oncology team at that time.
#2 Barrett's esophagus
Once Ms. Marcantel has recovered from surgery, we would recommend the use of proton-pump inhibitor therapy such as omeprazole 20-mg daily.  She should follow-up with her local physician for serial monitoring with a repeat EGD and biopsies within the next year in order to rule-out dysplastic changes and to determine long-term followup plans for the Barrett's esophagus.
Ms. Marcantel and her husband were in understanding and agreement with this plan.  All questions were answered.
FOLLOW-UP
Ms. Marcantel will follow-up after all tests and consults.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at Zuni Cooperative Hospital.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

